    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>E. E. Hilliard &amp; Company, a woollen goods manufacturer, was established in 1794 by Aaron Buckland.  Elisha E. Hilliard 
	  became part owner of the mills in 1831 and became sole owner in 1842.  Aaron Krock purchased the buildings in 1940 and the 
	  site was used to manufacture aircraft parts for Pratt and Whitney during World War II.  In 1949 the site was purchased by the 
	  Bezzini family and became a manufacturing plant for their Old Colony Furniture Company.</p>
      <p>The site was re-acquired by Hilliard Mills LLC in 2006 and renovated as a "premiere location for business," 
	  leasing office and business space.  It is a nationally listed historic site (see their website at 
	  
        
        <extref href="http://www.hilliardmills.com">http://www.hilliardmills.com</extref> for more information).</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The 
        
        <emph render="bold">E. E. Hilliard &amp; Company Records</emph> consist of correspondence, financial material, 
	  miscellaneous material, and 
	  ledgers. </p>
      <p>The bulk of the 
        
        <emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> and 
        
        <emph render="bold">Financial material</emph> 
(checkbooks, time books, bill and receipts) deals with the years 1850-1935, when the factory was at its 
	  peak production.  Several papers also concern smaller branches of the company, including the Hilliard Mills, the Charter Oak Co., 
	  the Eagle Mill Co., and the Vernon Mills Co.</p>
      <p>The 
        
        <emph render="bold">Miscellaneous</emph> material includes notes on the history of E. E. Hillard &amp; Co. as well as some specific notes on papers 
	  in the collection.  Of particular interest is the sample book, containing swatches of different woollen goods with notations, 
	  dated 1884.  There is also a set of dye formulas with representative samples, dated 1885.</p>
      <p>
        <emph render="bold">Ledgers</emph> span more than eighty years of the company and include a few from the smaller branches.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>Material is in alphabetical order by type of material; within that, most material is organized chronologically.</p>
    </arrangement>
